column12: INTEGRATED CIRCUIT STRUCTURE WITH SECURITY FEATURE
column13: An integrated circuit (10) is formed with at least a top circuit layer (20) having a passivation layer (19) provided on and around the circuit layer (20). A shielding layer (18) is provided on the passivation layer (19) and a top passivation layer (17) is provided on the shielding layer (18). The shielding layer (18) and the passivation layer (19) are provided with respective corresponding apertures (13 and 16) which are formed over essential portions of the top circuit layer (20) so as to expose the top circuit layer (20). The top circuit layer (20) and the shielding layer (18) have the same or similar chemical properties and the shielding layer (18) is opaque to light so that the top circuit layer (20) cannot be simply analysed by visible inspection. Thus, attempts to remove the shielding layer (18) by chemical means, for example etching, will also remove or damage the top circuit layer (20) exposed through the apertures (16 and 13).

column12: Strap adjuster
column13: A strap adjuster comprises an adjustor body 10 having a belt guide surface 36, and a pivotally mounted clamping member 38 with an eccentric clamping surface 42. The clearance between the guide surface 36 and the clamping surface 42 reduces with angular movement of the clamping member. Movement of a strap 50 in one direction causes angular movement of the clamping member 38 in a direction to reduce this clearance so as to wedge the strap between the clamping surface 42 and the guide surface 36 thereby inhibiting further movement of the strap 50 in said one direction. An additional guide member 48 is mounted on the adjuster body 10 so as to hold the strap 50 out of engagement with the clamping surface 42 when the clamping member 38 is displaced from its clamping position by more than a predetermined angle, as shown in Figure 5. <IMAGE>

column12: Semiconductor switching circuit
column13: The circuit is for switching an alternating current supply to a load and comprises a thyristor (1, 2, 3) with a first terminal connected to the load and a second terminal connected with an alternating current supply and a gate electrode which is connected with the output of a gate control circuit, an input of said gate control circuit being connected to said alternating current supply and a switching means (29) included in the gate control circuit operable to enable current to flow through the gate circuit, the gate control circuit providing an output signal which turns on the thyristor to connect the supply to the load upon said alternating current flowing through said gate control circuit. In one example, the load comprises a three phase motor 30 connected to the supply through three triacs 1,2,3. The triacs are fired by a circuit which includes a start button 25, a stop button 24, and thyristor 29 and a transformer 19. The invention thus provides a semi-conductor switching circuit of "solid state" construction which enables stopping and starting of, for example, a three phase motor and which overcomes one of the major problems of hitherto available mechanical motor starters, that is, contact wear due to repeated sparking of the contacts resulting from the inductive load being switched. <IMAGE>

column12: Salient pole rotor with embedded heat sink
column13: An electrical machine rotor (200b) of the salient pole type has a number of wound poles (100b), each pole's principle axis being radially oriented with respect to the rotational centre of the rotor. Each pole comprises a magnetic core with layers of conductor (CS1) wound around it. The pole windings incorporate heat sinks in the form of cooling tongues (204a), arranged so that part (208a) of each tongue lies between adjacent conductor layers in the windings. The parts of the tongues (208a) between the conductor layers extend parallel to the principle axis of each pole, whereas the other parts (210a) project into cooling channels (203) between adjacent poles, where they are exposed to cooling air. The parts (210a) of the cooling tongues exposed to cooling air may have their surfaces ribbed, finned or otherwise roughened to increase heat transfer to the cooling air.

column12: Packaging integrated circuits
column13: An integrated circuit (12) is mounted on a flag portion (11) of a leadframe. The leadframe also includes lead posts (10) to which are connected electrical connectors or bond wires (13) extending between the posts (10) and the integrated circuit (12). A plastic package (A) is moulded around the lead posts (10), the flag (11), the integrated circuit (12) and the bond wires (13). A polymer material is coated on all surfaces exposed prior to moulding of the package (A). The polymer material used for this encapsulation is is of very low molecular weight and viscosity and provides protection of the integrated circuit from corrosion by being chemisorbed onto its surface. This effectively seals any problem in the integrity of the passivation layer preventing moisture ingress, collection and therefore corrosion. <IMAGE>

column12: Indirect branch target predictor that prevents speculation if mispredict is expected
column13: In one embodiment, a processor implements an indirect branch target predictor to predict target addresses of indirect branch instructions. The indirect branch target predictor may store target addresses generated during previous executions of indirect branches, and may use the stored target addresses as predictions for current indirect branches. The indirect branch target predictor may also store a validation tag corresponding to each stored target address. The validation tag may be compared to similar data corresponding to the current indirect branch being predicted. If the validation tag does not match, the indirect branch is presumed to be mispredicted (since the branch target address actually belongs to a different instruction). The indirect branch target predictor may inhibit speculative execution subsequent to the mispredicted indirect branch until the redirect is signalled for the mispredicted indirect branch.

column12: Kindersicherheitssitz
column13: A child safety seat for use in a vehicle has a seat body (10) and a harness (16-22) including a pair of shoulder straps (16, 18) which extend through respective slots (28, 32, 36) in the seat back (26) to a mechanism for adjusting the length of the shoulder straps (16, 18). The height at which the shoulder straps (16, 18) project from the seat back (26) can be varied by threading them through different slots. A pad (50) is slidably mounted on each shoulder strap (16, 18) and has a cover formed of high friction material on the side (52) thereof facing the child occupant's body. A tether strap (54) has one end attached to each pad (50) and projects through the same slot (28, 32, 36) in the seat back (26) as the corresponding shoulder strap (16, 18) for limiting movement of the corresponding chest pad (50) along the shoulder strap (16, 18) to a predetermined limit distance away from the seat back (26). Such limit distance increases as the height at which the shoulder straps (16, 18) project from the seat back (26) is increased. <IMAGE> <IMAGE>

column12: HEAT EXCHANGER OF THE SHELL AND THE TUBE TYPE
column13: 1,242,359. Tubular heat exchangers; Incinerators. DORR-OLIVER Inc. 5 Feb., 1970, No. 5537/70. Headings F4B and F4S. A heat exchange unit 10 for preheating combustion air to be supplied as underblast to a fluidized bed type refuse incinerator 11 comprises an L-shaped tube bundle 34 of loop tubes connected to a tube plate T and contained within a easing having an inlet 47 and outlet 48 for hot combustion gases supplied from the incinerator 11. Air to be preheated is supplied to the lower chamber 61 of header 59 by a blower 12, is heated on passing through the loop tubes, and thereafter fed to the windbox 16 of the incinerator from the upper header chamber 62. Horizontal transverse support bars 65 are provided for securing the horizontal outlet portion of each loop tube against lateral deflection while allowing unrestricted thermal elongation. The tube bundle comprises a plurality of vertical assemblies of loop tubes 53, 54, 55, proper spacing of these assemblies being ensured by means of inverted U-shaped spacer elements (67, Fig. 8). The casing corner section bounded by flanges 35, 36 is removable for inspection and cleaning purposes. Soot blowers 68a in the form of transversely extending blower tubes are provided for periodic cleaning of the tubes. The refuse incinerator 11 comprises a combustion chamber 15 separated from the windbox by a member 14. Material to be burnt, e.g. dewatered sewage sludge, is fed at 17 into the fluidized bed B of sand. A burner R provides hot fluidizing gas at start-up whereafter, when combustion in the bed is self-sustaining, preheated combustion air from the heat exchange unit 10 provides the bulk of the fluidizing gas. Supplementary fuel may be added if required.

column12: Heat transfer element and tuyere for fluidized bed reactor

column12: Next fetch predictor training with hysteresis
column13: A system and method for efficient branch prediction. A processor includes two branch predictors. A first branch predictor quickly generates branch prediction data, such as a branch direction and a branch target address. The second branch predictor generates branch prediction data at a later time and with higher prediction accuracy. Control logic may determine whether the branch prediction data from each of the first and the second branch predictors match. If a mismatch occurs, the first predictor may be trained with the branch prediction data generated by the second branch predictor. A stored indication of hysteresis may indicate a given branch instruction exhibits a frequently alternating pattern regarding its branch direction. Such behavior may lead to consistent branch mispredictions due to the training is unable to keep up with the changing branch direction. When such a condition is determined to occur, the control logic may prevent training of the first predictor.

column12: TWO STAGE PROCESS FOR PRODUCING PURIFIED GAS
column13: The present invention provides a process for producing purified gas from a feed gas stream comprising methane and gaseous contaminants, the process comprising the steps of : 1) providing the feed gas stream; 2) cooling the feed gas stream to a temperature at which at least part of the feed gas stream is present in the liquid phase; 3) separating the cooled feed gas stream by means of cryogenic distillation into a bottom stream rich in contaminants and lean in methane, and into a top stream rich in methane and lean in gaseous contaminants, in which the bottom stream contains between 0.5 and 15 % of the methane present in the feed gas stream; 4) cooling the stream rich in methane to a temperature at which solid and/or liquid phase contaminants are formed; 5) introducing the cooled stream of step 4) into a gas/liquid/solids separation vessel, and 6) removing from the gas/liquid/solids separation vessel the purified gas and a stream rich in contaminants.

column12: Method and system of a microprocessor subtraction-division floating point divider
column13: The specification discloses a structure of and a method of operating a subtractive division (SD) cell where a portion of the partial remainder or estimated partial remainder directly indicates the next quotient digit. More particularly, by sufficiently constraining the prescaled range for each possible divisor, only a few bits of the partial remainder (the exact number dependent upon the radix), along with their related carries (if any), directly indicate the value of the next quotient digit. Because fewer bits of the partial remainder are needed to make this determination than needed in related art devices, and further because no look-up table or hard-coded decision tree is required, calculation time within each SD cell is shorter than related art devices. Having a shorter calculation time within each SD cell allows for either completion of a greater number of SD cells within each clock cycle, or completion of the calculation to full precision in less time.
column15: BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J;;SAMUDRALA SRIDHAR

column12: Indirect Branch Target Predictor that Prevents Speculation if Mispredict Is Expected
column13: In one embodiment, a processor implements an indirect branch target predictor to predict target addresses of indirect branch instructions. The indirect branch target predictor may store target addresses generated during previous executions of indirect branches, and may use the stored target addresses as predictions for current indirect branches. The indirect branch target predictor may also store a validation tag corresponding to each stored target address. The validation tag may be compared to similar data corresponding to the current indirect branch being predicted. If the validation tag does not match, the indirect branch is presumed to be mispredicted (since the branch target address actually belongs to a different instruction). The indirect branch target predictor may inhibit speculative execution subsequent to the mispredicted indirect branch until the redirect is signalled for the mispredicted indirect branch.
column15: BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J;;GUNNA RAMESH

column12: Improvements in or relating to data integrity
column13: A method and system for verifying transactions involves assigning trusted status to a subset of users 101. The trusted users 102 may be private organisations, individuals, government entities, regulars and/or other stakeholders. The trusted users 102 define a centralised root of trust. One or more tokens are issued from the centralised root of trust to users 101. A transaction is submitted involving at least one token for verification by each of the trusted users 102. It is determined whether or not a transaction is centrally verified based on whether or not a predetermined proportion of the trusted users 102 have individually verified the transaction or not. The proportion may be a simple majority or may be variable. If the transaction is centrally verified the transaction is recorded to a centralised ledger 104. If the transaction is not centrally verified, the transaction is not recorded to the centralised ledger 104.

column12: Microprocessor floating point divider
column13: The specification discloses a structure of and a method of operating a subtractive division (SD) cell where a portion of the partial remainder or estimated partial remainder directly indicates the next quotient digit. More particularly, by sufficiently constraining the prescaled range for each possible divisor, only a few bits of the partial remainder (the exact number dependent upon the radix), along with their related carries (if any), directly indicate the value of the next quotient digit. Because fewer bits of the partial remainder are needed to make this determination than needed in related art devices, and further because no look-up table or hard-coded decision tree is required, calculation time within each SD cell is shorter than related art devices. Having a shorter calculation time within each SD cell allows for either completion of a greater number of SD cells within each clock cycle, or completion of the calculation to full precision in less time.

column12: TWO STAGE PROCESS FOR PRODUCING PURIFIED GAS
column13: The present invention provides a process for producing purified gas from a feed gas stream comprising methane and gaseous contaminants, the process comprising the steps of: 1) providing the feed gas stream; 2) cooling the feed gas stream to a temperature at which at least part of the feed gas stream is present in the liquid phase; 3) separating the cooled feed gas stream by means of cryogenic distillation into a bottom stream rich in contaminants and lean in methane, and into a top stream rich in methane and lean in gaseous contaminants, in which the bottom stream contains between 0.5 and 15% of the methane present in the feed gas stream; 4) cooling the stream rich in methane to a temperature at which solid and/or liquid phase contaminants are formed; 5) introducing the cooled stream of step 4) into a gas/liquid/solids separation vessel, and 6) removing from the gas/liquid/solids separation vessel the purified gas and a stream rich in contaminants.

column12: HEAT EXCHANGER FOR FLUIDIZED BED REACTOR
column13: A fluidized bed reactor is provided with vertically oriented heat exchange coils for controlling the temperature of the fluidized bed. Tuyere elements discharge fluidizing gas at a level substantially above the constriction plate. The bed solids below the level of the tuyere ports constitute a static layer during fluidization and the lower return bends of the heat exchange coils are embedded in this layer and so are shielded from erosion by the fluidized solids of the bed proper.

column12: Next fetch predictor training with hysteresis
column13: A system and method for efficient branch prediction. A processor includes two branch predictors. A first branch predictor quickly generates branch prediction data, such as a branch direction and a branch target address. The second branch predictor generates branch prediction data at a later time and with higher prediction accuracy. Control logic may determine whether the branch prediction data from each of the first and the second branch predictors match. If a mismatch occurs, the first predictor may be trained with the branch prediction data generated by the second branch predictor. A stored indication of hysteresis may indicate a given branch instruction exhibits a frequently alternating pattern regarding its branch direction. Such behavior may lead to consistent branch mispredictions due to the training is unable to keep up with the changing branch direction. When such a condition is determined to occur, the control logic may prevent training of the first predictor.
column15: BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J;;GUNNA RAMESH B

column12: Store Hit Load Predictor
column13: In one embodiment, a processor implements a store hit load predictor. The store hit load predictor is configured to monitor fetched ops in the processor, and is configured to detect stores that may have previously caused store hit load events. The store hit load predictor is configured to predict that the store will cause a store hit load event again, and is further configured to monitor subsequent fetched ops for the load. The store hit load predictor may locate the load using, e.g., an offset from the store to the load in the code sequence. In response to locating the load, the store hit load predictor may create a dependency of the load on the store, preventing the load from executing out of order with respect to the store. A store hit load event may be avoided in this fashion, at least in some cases.
column15: BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J;;MYLIUS JOHN H

column12: NEXT FETCH PREDICTOR TRAINING ACCOMPANIED BY HYSTERESIS
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a system and method for performing efficient branch prediction.SOLUTION: A processor includes two branch predictors. The first branch predictor quickly generates branch prediction data such as a branch direction and a branch target address. The second branch predictor generates branch prediction data with much higher prediction accuracy in the following time. A control logic determines whether or not the branch prediction data from the first and second branch predictors is coincident with each other. When the branch prediction data is not coincident, the first predictor is trained with the branch prediction data generated by the second branch predictor. An indication in which hysteresis is stored indicates that a predetermined branch instruction shows a pattern to be frequently replaced concerning the branch direction. Such a behavior causes consistent branch prediction mistakes since training cannot follow up a changing branch direction.
column15: ANDREW J BEAUMONT-SMITH;;RAMESH B GUNNA

column12: UNCOUPLING PROTEIN 4 (UCP-4) AND METHODS OF USE
column13: A novel uncoupling protein, which we have designated UCP-4, that is expressed in various tissues, including brain, heart, pancreas, and muscle tissue, and nucleic acid molecules which encode for said novel protein, are described. Methods of screening for compounds that regulate the expression and the activity of UCP-4 are described, as well as methods of treating diseases or conditions in which the regulation of thermogenesis or respiratory ATP synthesis is desired. Such conditions include obesity, diabetes, malignant hyperthermia, and fever. The construction of cell lines that express UCP-4 is also described.

column12: NEXT FETCH PREDICTOR TRAINING WITH HYSTERESIS
column13: PURPOSE: A method for training the next withdrawal predictor with histories is provided to prevent consistent branch prediction errors by following a branch direction having changed training. CONSTITUTION: A first branch predictor(150) provides the display of histories of a branch command and generates first branch prediction data about the branch command. A second branch predictor(130) generates second branch prediction data about the branch command. A control logic unit generates an output based on the display of the histories and the first and second branch prediction data in response to a determination about mismatch between the first and second branch prediction data. The output is used for determining whether to train the first prediction predictor. [Reference numerals] (100) Processor pipeline; (110) Address selection; (112) Incrementer; (120) i-cache; (130) Next withdrawal predictor; (132) Next withdrawal table; (134) Next withdrawal control logic; (140) Decode unit; (150) Branch predictor; (160) Command processing unit; (AA) Pipe stage 1; (BB) Pipe stage 2; (CC) Pipe stage 3; (DD) Pipe stage 4; (EE) Pipe stage N

column12: VIDEOKODER.
column13: A coder assembles bursts of blocks of image data (eg transform coded coefficients) and associated overhead data into a sequence of data which are then transmitted. Both the transform coded coefficients and the overhead data are initially stored in separate FIFO memory stores (21)(22). The blocks of transform coded coefficients have a 'last coefficient' flag accompanying the last coefficient, and the overhead information contains a unique word SWITCH, after the header information but before the 'end-of-block' flag. The 'last coefficient' flag and the SWITCH word are recognised by a toggle controller (29) which controls the reading of the stores so that the coefficient data and overhead data are selectively passed to a buffer (30) in a desired sequence. The buffer (30) is followed by a variable length coder (31) which supplies the output of the coder at a constant bit rate. Provision (34-38) is made to calculate the quantity of output data represented at any time by the contents of the buffer and the result is used to control the rate of generation of image data.

column12: PULSE MODULE FOR BREATHING ASSISTANCE APPARATUS
column13: A device (7), or a respiratory support system that includes a device, and a method of using the device, for introducing pulses to a patient breathing cycle which is at least partially assisted by a respiratory support system. The device has a body, with a passage running through the body between the inlet (8) and the outlet (9). A valve (15) is located in the passage, and cycles between open and at least partially closed. The cycle frequency is greater than the frequency of the patient breathing cycle. The device is connected to the patient respiratory support system in such a manner that at least a portion of the expiratory gases from a patient pass through the passage (12, 13).

column12: Roller impeller extrusion press - in which slip between the roller and die is monitored to indicate blockage
column13: In an extruder in which material is fed into the nip between a press roll and a die having extrusion orifices, through which the material is forced, either the roll or die is positively driven causing the other of the roll or die to rotate, and slip between the roll and die is detected. When the slip, or the rate of change of slip, attains a predetermined value the feed of material to the nip is varied. Used partic. in the extrusion of animal feed pellets. Presses can easily block, choke, or flood, necessitating plant shut down to remove material from the nip, or even removal of the die to clear the orifices. By monitoring slip, conditions leading to blockage of the die can easily be detected and remedied.

The `last coefficient` flag and the SWITCH word are recognized by a toggle controller (29) which controls the reading of the stores so that the coefficient data and overhead data are selectively passed to a buffer (30) in a desired sequence. The buffer (30) is followed by a variable length coder (31) which supplies the output of the coder at a constant bit rate. Provision (34-38) is made to calculate the quantity of output data represented at any time by the contents of the buffer and the result is used to control the rate of generation of image data.

column12: Video coder
column13: A coder assembles bursts of blocks of image data (eg transform coded coefficients) and associated overhead data into a sequence of data which are then transmitted. Both the transform coded coefficients and the overhead data are initially stored in separate FIFO memory stores (21)(22). The blocks of transform coded coefficients have a 'last coefficient' flag accompanying the last coefficient, and the overhead information contains a unique word SWITCH, after the header information but before the 'end-of-block' flag. The 'last coefficient' flag and the SWITCH word are recognised by a toggle controller (29) which controls the reading of the stores so that the coefficient data and overhead data are selectively passed to a buffer (30) in a desired sequence. The buffer (30) is followed by a variable length coder (31) which supplies the output of the coder at a constant bit rate. Provision (34-38) is made to calculate the quantity of output data represented at any time by the contents of the buffer and the result is used to control the rate of generation of image data.

column12: TREATING A CRUDE AND NATURAL GAS STREAM
column13: A process for treating a crude and natural gas stream, which at least comprises the steps of: (a) passing a crude and natural gas stream ( 10 ) through an inlet ( 12 ) into a stabilization unit ( 14 ) to provide a stabilizer content ( 20 ); (b) passing an overhead gaseous stream ( 30 ) separated from the stabilizer content ( 20 ) through a first outlet ( 16 ); and (c) passing a bottom stream ( 40 ) comprising crude liquid hydrocarbons separated from the stabilizer content ( 20 ) and free water through a second outlet ( 18 ).

column12: MAINTAINING THE INTEGRITY OF AN EXECUTION RETURN ADDRESS STACK
column13: A processor and method for maintaining the integrity of an execution return address stack (RAS). The execution RAS is maintained in an accurate state by storing information regarding branch instructions in a branch information table. The first time a branch instruction is executed, an entry is allocated and populated in the table. If the branch instruction is re-executed, a pointer address is retrieved from the corresponding table entry and the execution RAS pointer is repositioned to the retrieved pointer address. The execution RAS can also be used to restore a speculative RAS due to a mis-speculation.

column12: MEANS AND METHODS FOR INFLUENCING THE STABILITY OF ANTIBODY PRODUCING CELLS
column13:
The invention provides methods for increasing the replicative life span and/or stability of an antibody producing cell, comprising 
- providing said antibody producing cell with a compound capable of directly or indirectly enhancing BCL6 expression and/or culturing said antibody producing cell in the presence of a compound capable of directly or indirectly enhancing BCL6 expression; and 
- directly or indirectly increasing the amount of Bcl-xL or another anti-apoptotic gene expression product within said antibody producing cell. Stable antibody producing cells and cell lines are also provided, as well as methods for producing antibodies using such cells and/or cell lines.

column12: NOVEL UNCOUPLING PROTEIN AND METHODS OF USE
column13: A novel uncoupling protein, which we have designated UCP-3, that is expressed in skeletal muscle and brown adipose tissue (BAT), and nucleic acid molecules which encode for said novel protein, are described. Methods of screening for compounds that regulate the expression and the activity of UCP-3 are described, as well as methods of treating diseases or conditions in which the regulation of thermogenesis or respiratory ATP synthesis is desired. Such conditions include obesity, diabetes, malignant hyperthermia, and fever. The construction of cell lines that express UCP-3 is also described.

column12: High resolution digital video colposcope with built-in polarized led illumination and computerized clinical data management system
column13: This invention uses LEDs and cross-polarization to produce bright, high- resolution digital images, both with and without glint (which adversely affects the clarity of standard colposcopic images), as well as streaming video at lower resolution. column12: Maintaining the integrity of an execution return address stack
column13: A processor and method for maintaining the integrity of an execution return address stack (RAS). The execution RAS is maintained in an accurate state by storing information regarding branch instructions in a branch information table. The first time a branch instruction is executed, an entry is allocated and populated in the table. If the branch instruction is re-executed, a pointer address is retrieved from the corresponding table entry and the execution RAS pointer is repositioned to the retrieved pointer address. The execution RAS can also be used to restore a speculative RAS due to a mis-speculation.

column12: MEANS AND METHODS FOR INFLUENCING THE STABILITY OF ANTIBODY PRODUCING CELLS
column13: Provided is an in vitro method for influencing the stability of an antibody producing cell, wherein the BCL6 expression is enhanced by expression of an exogenous BCL6 coding sequence and/or by providing the antigen producing cell with STAT5 directly or via expression of an exogenous STAT5 coding sequence and or culturing the antigen producing cell with IL-2 and/or IL-4; and increasing Bcl-xL expression by various means. The antigen producing cells can be stable for at least one week and as long as six months. Further provided are antibodies obtained by the method.

column12: Behandling av en ragass- og naturstrom
column13: Fremgangsmåte for å behandle rågass- og naturgasstrøm, omfattende minst trinnene: (a) en rågass- og naturgasstrøm (10) føres gjennom et innløp (12) inn i en stabiliseringsenhet (14) for å oppnå et stabilisatorinnhold (20), (b) en gassformig toppstrøm (30) skilt fra stabilisatorinnholdet (20) føres gjennom et første utløp (16), og (c) en bunnstrøm (40) som omfatter flytende råhydrokarboner skilt fra stabilisatorinnholdet (20) og fritt vann, føres gjennom et andre utløp (18).

column12: High resolution digital video colposcope with built-in polarized LED illumination and computerized clinical data management system
column13: This invention uses LEDs and cross-polarization to produce bright, high-resolution digital images, both with and without glint (which adversely affects the clarity of standard colposcopic images), as well as streaming video at lower resolution. The invention allows for deeper layers of the tissue to be more efficiently visualized at multiple magnifications, thereby enhancing the invention's diagnostic capabilities, and it includes a focusing subsystem and a computerized data management system to archive and annotate still image data.

column12: ULTRASONIC MONITORING TECHNIQUE FOR CONTAINERS AND APPARATUS TO CARRY IT OUT
column13: The invention provides an apparatus and method for fill level monitoring in which the height of contents in a container (10) is monitored. The apparatus comprises an ultrasound receiver (30) and signal processing means (50-56) adapted to receive signals from the receiver, the arrangement being such that the signal processing means (50-56) identifies a first signal (32), in use, which is representative of a wavefront (26) transmitted through the contents of the container (10) independently of the height of the contents in the container (10), and a second signal (34) that is representative of a wavefront (24) that is reflected from the interface (22) between the surface of the contents in the container (10) and the environment above the contents, and in which the signal processing means (50-56) uses the difference in travel time for the two wavefronts (24, 26) to provide a measurement of the level of the contents in the container (10). A plasma generation system comprising a pulsed laser (99) and a target (101) in front of the container (102) is also disclosed, the plasma (103) creating ultrasound in the container (102).

column12: NON-MECHANICAL CONTACT ULTRASOUND SYSTEM FOR MONITORING CONTENTS OF A MOVING CONTAINER
column13: A non-contact apparatus for monitoring the contents of a container, especially but not exclusively for quality control monitoring purposes associated with high speed packaging processes, comprises non-contact ultrasound generation means, adapted so as to generate an ultrasound signal within the container (1). A non-contact detection scheme is employed to enable the contents of the container to be monitored by analysing ultrasound signals that have propagated through or round the container (1) either transmitted through or reflected from the containers contents. In use, the apparatus may be adapted to provide information about container fill level (h) or the presence or absence of an insert (14) such as a head forming device by analysing the measured signal profiles generated by the ultrasound detection means (3).

column12: Debug Trace of Cache Memory Requests
column13: An apparatus includes a plurality of processor circuits, a cache memory circuit, and a trace control circuit. The trace control circuit may be configured, in response to activation of a mode to record information indicative of program execution of at least one processor circuit of the plurality of processor circuits, to monitor memory requests transmitted between ones of the plurality of processor circuits and the cache memory circuit, and then to select a particular memory request of monitored memory requests using an arbitration algorithm. The trace control circuit may be further configured to allocate space in a trace buffer to the particular memory request, and to store, in the trace buffer, information associated with the particular memory request.

column12: Coprocessor with Distributed Register
column13: In an embodiment, a coprocessor includes multiple processing elements arranged in a grid of one or more rows and one or more columns. A given processing element includes an arithmetic/logic unit (ALU) circuit configured to perform an ALU operation specified by an instruction executable by the coprocessor, wherein the ALU circuit is configured to produce a result. The given processing element further comprises a first memory coupled to the execute circuit. The first memory is configured to store results generated by the given processing element. The first memory includes a portion of a result memory implemented by the coprocessor, wherein locations in the result memory are specifiable as destination operands of instructions executable by the coprocessor. The portion of the result memory implemented by the first memory is the portion of the result memory that the given processing element is capable of updating.

column12: Inflatable flotation assembly.
column13: An inflatable flotation assembly includes a compressed gas cylinder (10) stored inside a split housing the parts (12,13) of which are held together by a releasable pivot (15) on one end and an interlocked pivoted arm at the other end which engages a flexible tab (17) aligned against the gas cylinder. The arm (43) overlies the housing to engage the releasable pivot and when unclasped from this engagement will rotate to pierce the cylinder (10) by deflecting the tab (17). Thereafter the expansion of a flotation bladder separates the housing while the arm remains interlocked to the tab to control the rate of gas release into the bladder by the angular inertia of the arm around its pivot.

column12: Coprocessor synchronizing instruction suppression
column13: An instruction set architecture including instructions for a processor and instructions for a coprocessor may include synchronizing instructions that may be used to begin and end instruction sequences that include coprocessor instructions (coprocessor sequences). If a terminating synchronizing instruction is followed by an initial synchronizing instruction and the pair are detected in the coprocessor concurrently, the coprocessor may suppress execution of the pair of instructions.
column15: KESIRAJU ADITYA;;BHUYAR RAJDEEP L;;CHACHICK RAN A;;BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J

column12: Coprocessor Register Renaming
column13: A coprocessor with register renaming is disclosed. An apparatus includes a plurality of processors and a coprocessor respectively configured to execute processor instructions and coprocessor instructions. The coprocessor receives coprocessor instructions from ones of the processors. The coprocessor includes an array of processing elements and a result register set comprising storage elements respectively distributed within the array of processing elements. For a given member of the array of processing elements, a corresponding storage element is configured to store coprocessor instruction results generated by the given member. The result register set implements a plurality of contexts to store respective coprocessor states corresponding to coprocessor instructions received from different processors. Based on a determination that one of the contexts is inactive, the coprocessor is configured to store coprocessor instruction results corresponding to an active context within storage elements of the result register set corresponding to the inactive context.
column15: CHACHICK RAN AHARON;;KESIRAJU ADITYA;;BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J;;LEE JONG-SUK

column12: Coprocessors with bypass optimization, variable grid architecture, and fused vector operations
column13: In an embodiment, a coprocessor may include a bypass indication which identifies execution circuitry that is not used by a given processor instruction, and thus may be bypassed. The corresponding circuitry may be disabled during execution, preventing evaluation when the output of the circuitry will not be used for the instruction. In another embodiment, the coprocessor may implement a grid of processing elements in rows and columns, where a given coprocessor instruction may specify an operation that causes up to all of the processing elements to operate on vectors of input operands to produce results. Implementations of the coprocessor may implement a portion of the processing elements. The coprocessor control circuitry may be designed to operate with the full grid or partial grid, reissuing instructions in the partial grid case to perform the requested operation. In still another embodiment, the coprocessor may be able to fuse vector mode operations.

column12: ION MOBILITY METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR IDENTIFYING AND/OR CHARACTERISING A SAMPLE COMPOUND
column13: A method of and apparatus for identifying and/or characterising a sample that may incorporate two or more isomeric or isobaric compounds such as hydroxylated metabolites. The method involves modelling an ensemble of possible structures for each of two or more known isomeric or isobaric compounds, calculating a theoretical collision cross-section for each modelled structure, averaging the calculated values for each known compound to provide a theoretical collision cross-section value for each known compound. A travelling wave ion mobility cell is used to measuring a collision cross-section value for the sample compound and the measured value is then compared with the theoretical values to identify which of the two or more known compounds the sample compound most closely resembles.

column12: SAFETY SEAT FOR CHILD
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To prevent non-desirable movement of a seat for a child relative to a vehicle.

SOLUTION: The safety seat for the child used for the vehicle is provided with a seat body (10) having a seat part (14) and a back rest part (16). A guide (52) provided on the seat body (10) forms a strap passage for a strap (50) of the seat belt of the vehicle for fixing the seat body (10) to the seat of the vehicle. A strap deflection means (62) becomes movable between a first position left from the strap passage and a second position where the strap (50) is deflected and tensionedly stretched.

column12: An attachment for a hair care appliance
column13: An attachment for a hair care appliance includes an air inlet (101, fig.4) for receiving an airflow from the hair care appliance, a main body (103, fig.4) arranged to receive the airflow from the air inlet, and a plurality of protrusions 112a-d arranged in a row. At least some of the protrusions are hollow. Each hollow protrusion extends from, and is configured to receive airflow from, the main body. Each hollow protrusion includes an air outlet 114. Each air outlet includes a through-hole 120a-c in a surface of the respective hollow protrusion and is arranged to emit airflow in an emittance direction non-orthogonal to the surface of the hollow protrusion around the through-hole. Each respective air outlet faces a neighbouring protrusion in the row. The attachment may include a plurality of solid protrusions 111a-d which may be arranged interstitially with respect to the hollow protrusions. A portion of the protrusion (1111k, fig 10a) may redirect flow emitted from the air outlets. Preferably, a portion of the protrusion surface (130, fig.4) is free from outlets.

column12: COMPOUND FOR PREVENTION OR TREATMENT OF A SKIN CANCER OR SKIN PRECANCER
column13: The present invention relates, inter alia, to a method of preventing or treating skin cancer or skin precancer, the method comprising locally administering to the skin of a subject in need thereof an effective amount of a compound of Formula (I) or a prodrug thereof, Formula (I) wherein the subject is being administered an immunosuppressant agent that binds to FKBP12. The agent that binds to FKBP12 may be tacrolimus. The invention also relates to methods of preventing or treating a skin condition, disorder or disease associated with administration of an immunosuppressant agent that binds to FKBP12, and to uses of the compound of Formula (I) in treating skin cancer or skin precancer, or a skin condition, disorder or disease associated with administration of an immunosuppressant agent that binds to FKBP12.

column12: 피부암 또는 피부 전암의 예방 또는 치료를 위한 화합물
column13: 본 발명은 특히 피부암 또는 피부 전암의 예방 또는 치료를 필요로 하는 대상체의 피부에 유효량의 화학식 (I)의 화합물 또는 그의 전구약물을 국부적으로 투여하는 것을 포함하는, 피부암 또는 피부 전암을 예방 또는 치료하는 방법이며, 여기서 대상체는 FKBP12에 결합하는 면역억제제를 투여받고 있는 것인 방법에 관한 것이다. TIFFpct00023.tif5255 FKBP12에 결합하는 작용제는 타크롤리무스일 수 있다. 본 발명은 또한 FKBP12에 결합하는 면역억제제의 투여와 연관된 피부 병태, 장애 또는 질환을 예방 또는 치료하는 방법, 및 피부암 또는 피부 전암, 또는 FKBP12에 결합하는 면역억제제의 투여와 연관된 피부 병태, 장애 또는 질환을 치료하는데 있어서 화학식 (I)의 화합물의 용도에 관한 것이다.

column12: Outer product engine
column13: In an embodiment, an outer product engine is configured to perform outer product operations. The outer product engine may perform numerous multiplication operations in parallel on input vectors, in an embodiment, generating a resulting outer product matrix. In an embodiment, the outer product engine may be configured to accumulate results in a result matrix, performing fused multiply add (FMA) operations to produce the outer product elements (multiply) and to accumulate the outer product elements with previous elements from the result matrix memory (add). A processor may fetch outer product instructions, and may transmit the instructions to the outer product engine when the instructions become non-speculative in an embodiment. The processor may be configured to retire the outer product instructions responsive to transmitting them to the outer product engine.

column12: Computation engine with extract instructions to minimize memory access
column13: In an embodiment, a computation engine may offload work from a processor (e.g. a CPU) and efficiently perform computations such as those used in LSTM and other workloads at high performance. In an embodiment, the computation engine may perform computations on input vectors from input memories in the computation engine, and may accumulate results in an output memory within the computation engine. The input memories may be loaded with initial vector data from memory, incurring the memory latency that may be associated with reading the operands. Compute instructions may be performed on the operands, generating results in an output memory. One or more extract instructions may be supported to move data from the output memory to the input memory, permitting additional computation on the data in the output memory without moving the results to main memory.

column12: Optical signal modulation device.
column13: An optical signal modulation device comprises first and second optical waveguides (1,2) fabricated on Z cut lithium niobate. The waveguides (1,2) are connected at one end to an optical signal splitter (7) and at the other end to a Y coupler (11). The output of the Y coupler (11) is connected to a single mode optical fibre (13). A first pair of modulator electrodes (3,4) are positioned across the waveguides (1,2) to cause relative phase shifts between signals in the two optical waveguides (1,2) in response to a first control signal V₁. These relative phase shifts are caused in both TM mode and TE mode signals. The device also includes a second pair of bias electrodes (14, 15) arranged to cause a relative phase shift between signals of the TE mode only whereby the transfer characteristics of the two modes may be shifted relatively to one another in use in accordance with the second control function.

column12: DISPOSITIVO DE MODULACION DE SEÑAL OPTICA.
column13: DISPOSITIVO DE MODULACION DE SEÑAL OPTICA QUE CONSTA DE UNA PRIMERA Y UNA SEGUNDA GUIAS DE ONDA OPTICA (1,2) DE NIOBATO DE LITIO DE CORTE Z. LAS GUIAS DE ONDA (1,2) VAN CONECTADAS POR UN EXTREMO A UN DIVISOR DE SEÑAL OPTICA (7) Y POR EL OTRO A UN ACOPLADOR Y (11). LA SALIDA DEL ACOPLADOR Y (11) VA CONECTADA A UNA FIBRA OPTICA (13) DE UN SOLO MODO. UN PRIMER PAR DE ELECTRODOS MODULADORES (3,4) ESTAN SITUADOS EN LAS GUIAS DE ONDA (1,2) PARA PROVOCAR VARIACION DE FASE RELATIVA ENTRE SEÑALES DE LAS DOS GUIAS DE ONDA OPTICAS (1,2) EN RESPUESTA A UNA PRIMERA SEÑAL DE CONTROL V1. ESTAS VARIACIONES DE FASE SE PROVOCAN TANTO EN SEÑALES DE MODO MAGNETICO TRANSVERSAL COMO DE MODO ELECTRICO TRANSVERSAL. EL DISPOSITIVO INCLUYE TAMBIEN UN SEGUNDO PAR DE ELECTRODOS DE POLARIZACION (14,15) QUE PRODUCEN UNA VARIACION DE FASE RELATIVA SOLO ENTRE SEÑALES DE MODO ELECTRICO TRANSVERSAL, POR LO QUE LAS CARACTERISTICAS DE TRANSFERENCIA DE LOS DOS MODOS PUEDEN VARIARSE RELATIVAMENTE ENTRE SI DE ACUERDO CON LA SEGUNDA FUNCION DEL CONTROL.

column12: COPROCESSORS WITH BYPASS OPTIMIZATION, VARIABLE GRID ARCHITECTURE, AND FUSED VECTOR OPERATIONS
column13: In an embodiment, a coprocessor may include a bypass indication which identifies execution circuitry that is not used by a given processor instruction, and thus may be bypassed. The corresponding circuitry may be disabled during execution, preventing evaluation when the output of the circuitry will not be used for the instruction. In another embodiment, the coprocessor may implement a grid of processing elements in rows and columns, where a given coprocessor instruction may specify an operation that causes up to all of the processing elements to operate on vectors of input operands to produce results. Implementations of the coprocessor may implement a portion of the processing elements. The coprocessor control circuitry may be designed to operate with the full grid or partial grid, reissuing instructions in the partial grid case to perform the requested operation. In still another embodiment, the coprocessor may be able to fuse vector mode operations.

column13: 일 실시예에서, 코프로세서는 주어진 프로세서 명령어에 의해 사용되지 않는 실행 회로를 식별하는 바이패스 표시를 포함할 수 있고, 따라서 바이패스될 수 있다. 대응하는 회로는 실행 동안 디스에이블되어, 회로의 출력이 명령어에 사용되지 않을 때 평가를 방지할 수 있다. 다른 실시예에서, 코프로세서는 행들 및 열들에서 프로세싱 요소들의 그리드를 구현할 수 있고, 여기서 주어진 코프로세서 명령어는 최대 모든 프로세싱 요소들이 입력 피연산자들의 벡터들 상에서 동작하게 하여 결과들을 생성하는 동작을 특정할 수 있다. 코프로세서의 구현들은 프로세싱 요소들의 부분을 구현할 수 있다. 코프로세서 제어 회로는 전체 그리드 또는 부분 그리드로 동작하도록 설계되어, 요청된 동작을 수행하기 위해 부분 그리드 케이스 내의 명령어들을 재발행할 수 있다. 또 다른 실시예에서, 코프로세서는 벡터 모드 동작들을 융합시킬 수 있다.

column12: Split Scheduler
column13: In an embodiment, a scheduler implements a first dependency array that tracks dependencies on instruction operations (ops) within a distance N of a given op and which are short execution latency ops. Other dependencies are tracked in a second dependency array. The first dependency array may evaluate quickly, to support back-to-back issuance of short execution latency ops and their dependent ops. The second array may evaluate more slowly than the first dependency array.

column12: COPROCESSORS WITH BYPASS OPTIMIZATION, VARIABLE GRID ARCHITECTURE, AND FUSED VECTOR OPERATIONS
column13: In an embodiment, a coprocessor may include a bypass indication which identifies execution circuitry that is not used by a given processor instruction, and thus may be bypassed. The corresponding circuitry may be disabled during execution, preventing evaluation when the output of the circuitry will not be used for the instruction. In another embodiment, the coprocessor may implement a grid of processing elements in rows and columns, where a given coprocessor instruction may specify an operation that causes up to all of the processing elements to operate on vectors of input operands to produce results. Implementations of the coprocessor may implement a portion of the processing elements. The coprocessor control circuitry may be designed to operate with the full grid or partial grid, reissuing instructions in the partial grid case to perform the requested operation. In still another embodiment, the coprocessor may be able to fuse vector mode operations.

column12: Processor instruction issue throttling
column13: The invention relates to processor instruction issue throttling. A system and method for reducing power consumption through issue throttling of selected problematic instructions. A power throttle unit within a processor maintains instruction issue counts for associated instruction types. The instruction types may be a subset of supported instruction types executed by an execution core within the processor. The instruction types may be chosen based on high power consumption estimates for processing instructions of these types. The power throttle unit may determine a given instruction issue count exceeds a given threshold. In response, the power throttle unit may select given instruction types to limit a respective issue rate. The power throttle unit may choose an issue rate for each one of the selected given instruction types and limit an associated issue rate to a chosen issue rate. The selection of given instruction types and associated issue rate limits is programmable.

column12: processador e método de regulação de emissão de instruções de processador
column13: regulação de emissão de instruções de processador. a invenção refere-se a um sistema e método para reduzir o consumo de potência através de regulação de emissão de instruções problemáticas selecionadas. uma unidade de regulação de potência dentro de um processador mantém contagens de emissão de instruções para tipos de instrução associados. os tipos de instrução podem ser um subconjunto de tipos de instrução suportados executados por um núcleo de execução dentro do processador. os tipos de instrução podem ser escolhidos com base em estimativas de alto consumo de potência para processar as instruções destes tipos. a unidade de regulação de potência pode determinar que uma dada contagem de emissão de instrução excede um dado limite. em resposta, a unidade de regulação de potência pode selecionar dados tipos de instrução para limitar uma respectiva taxa de emissão. a unidade de regulação de potência pode escolher uma taxa de emissão para cada um dos dados tipos de instrução selecionados e limitar uma taxa de emissão associada para uma taxa de emissão escolhida. a seleção de dados tipos de instrução e limites de taxa de emissão associados é programável.

column12: PROCESSOR INSTRUCTION ISSUE THROTTLING
column13: PURPOSE: Processor command publication throttling is provided to control publication throttling of selected problematic commands, thereby efficiently reducing power consumption. CONSTITUTION: A scheduler(124) selects and publishes commands. An execution core receives and executes the commands. A power throttle unit(150) maintains a command publication count for a command type. When the command publication count exceeds a threshold value, the power throttle unit selects the command type for a limited command publication rate and selects a new publication rate for the command type. The power throttle unit performs selection based on a power throttle code written by the software. column12: Coprocessor Prefetcher
column13: A prefetcher for a coprocessor is disclosed. An apparatus includes a processor and a coprocessor that are configured to execute processor and coprocessor instructions, respectively. The processor and coprocessor instructions appear together in code sequences fetched by the processor, with the coprocessor instructions being provided to the coprocessor by the processor. The apparatus further includes a coprocessor prefetcher configured to monitor a code sequence fetched by the processor and, in response to identifying a presence of coprocessor instructions in the code sequence, capture the memory addresses, generated by the processor, of operand data for coprocessor instructions. The coprocessor is further configured to issue, for a cache memory accessible to the coprocessor, prefetches for data associated with the memory addresses prior to execution of the coprocessor instructions by the coprocessor.

column12: REGULAÇÃO DE EMISSÃO DE INSTRUÇÕES DE PROCESSADOR
column13: REGULAÇÃO DE EMISSÃO DE INSTRUÇÕES DE PROCESSADOR. A invenção refere-se a um sistema e método para reduzir o consumo de potência através de regulação de emissão de instruções problemáticas selecionadas. Uma unidade de regulação de potência dentro de um processador mantém contagens de emissão de instruções para tipos de instrução associados. Os tipos de instrução podem ser um subconjunto de tipos de instrução suportados executados por um núcleo de execução dentro do processador. Os tipos de instrução podem ser escolhidos com base em estimativas de alto consumo de potência para processar as instruções destes tipos. A unidade de regulação de potência pode determinar que uma dada contagem de emissão de instrução excede um dado limite. Em resposta, a unidade de regulação de potência pode selecionar dados tipos de instrução para limitar uma respectiva taxa de emissão. A unidade de regulação de potência pode escolher uma taxa de emissão para cada um dos dados tipos de instrução selecionados e limitar uma taxa de emissão associada para uma taxa de emissão escolhida. A seleção de dados tipos de instrução e limites de taxa de emissão associados é programável.

column15: BANNON PETER J;;BEAUMONT-SMITH ANDREW J;;GUNNA RAMESH;;LIEN WEI-HAN;;PATWARDHAN JAIDEV P;;LILLY BRIAN P;;WEN SHIH-CHIEH R;;YEH TSE-YU

column12: Combining write buffer with dynamically adjustable flush metrics
column13: In an embodiment, a combining write buffer is configured to maintain one or more flush metrics to determine when to transmit write operations from buffer entries. The combining write buffer may be configured to dynamically modify the flush metrics in response to activity in the write buffer, modifying the conditions under which write operations are transmitted from the write buffer to the next lower level of memory. For example, in one implementation, the flush metrics may include categorizing write buffer entries as "collapsed." A collapsed write buffer entry, and the collapsed write operations therein, may include at least one write operation that has overwritten data that was written by a previous write operation in the buffer entry. In another implementation, the combining write buffer may maintain the threshold of buffer fullness as a flush metric and may adjust it over time based on the actual buffer fullness.

column12: aparelho e método de buffer de escrita de combinação com medidas de esvaziamento dinamicamente ajustáveis.
column13: buffer de escrita de combinação com medidas de esvaziamento dinamicamente ajustáveis. a presente invenção refere-se a um buffer de escrita de combinação que, em uma modalidade, é configurado para manter uma ou mais medidas de esvaziamento para determinar quando é para transmitir operações de escrita a partir de entradas de buffer. o buffer de escrita de combinação pode ser configurado para modificar dinamicamente as medidas de esvaziamento, em resposta a uma atividade no buffer de escrita, modificando as condições segundo as quais as operações de escrita são transmitidas a partir do buffer de escrita para o próximo nível mais baixo de memória. por exemplo, em uma implementação, as medidas de esvaziamento podem incluir entradas de buffer de escrita de categorização, tais como "colapsado". uma entrada de buffer de escrita colapsado e as operações de escrita colapsadas ali podem incluir pelo menos uma operação de escrita que tenha dados sobrescritos que foram escritos por uma operação de escrita prévia na entrada de buffer. em uma outra implementação, a combinação do buffer de escrita pode manter o limite de ocupação plena de buffer como uma medida de esvaziamento e pode ajustá-lo ao longo do tempo, com base na ocupação plena de buffer real.

column12: COMBINING WRITE BUFFER WITH DYNAMICALLY ADJUSTABLE FLUSH METRICS
column13: PURPOSE: A combining write buffer with dynamically adjustable flush metrics is provided to determine the transmitting timing of writing operations from buffer entries by maintaining one or more flush metrics. CONSTITUTION: A controlling circuit monitors activities in a writing buffer(30). The controlling circuit modifies one or more flush metrics, which are maintained by the controlling circuit, by responding to the activities(34). The controlling circuit causes one or more writing operations from at least one buffer entry of the writing buffers by responding to the buffer fullness of the writing buffers and the flux metrics(38). The number of writing buffer entries is compared with the threshold value of the buffer fullness.

column12: IN SITU-GENERATED MICROFLUIDIC ISOLATION STRUCTURES, KITS AND METHODS OF USE THEREOF
column13: In situ-generated microfluidic isolation structures incorporating a solidified polymer network, methods of preparation and use, compositions and kits therefor are described. The in situ-generated isolation structures may be permanently or temporarily installed.

column12: Combining Write Buffer with Dynamically Adjustable Flush Metrics
column13: In an embodiment, a combining write buffer is configured to maintain one or more flush metrics to determine when to transmit write operations from buffer entries. The combining write buffer may be configured to dynamically modify the flush metrics in response to activity in the write buffer, modifying the conditions under which write operations are transmitted from the write buffer to the next lower level of memory. For example, in one implementation, the flush metrics may include categorizing write buffer entries as “collapsed.” A collapsed write buffer entry, and the collapsed write operations therein, may include at least one write operation that has overwritten data that was written by a previous write operation in the buffer entry. In another implementation, the combining write buffer may maintain the threshold of buffer fullness as a flush metric and may adjust it over time based on the actual buffer fullness.

column12: MICROFLUIDIC DEVICE FOR CULTURING BIOLOGICAL CELLS AND METHODS OF USE THEREOF

column15: BEAUMONT KRISTIN G;;DING NAN-LINDA;;KURZ VOLKER L S;;LIONBERGER TROY A;;LOWE RANDALL D JR;;MALLEO DANIELE;;MCFARLAND ANDREW W;;NEVILL J TANNER;;WANG XIAOHUA

column12: In situ-generated microfluidic isolation structures, kits and methods of use thereof
column13: In situ-generated microfluidic isolation structures incorporating a solidified polymer network, methods of preparation and use, compositions and kits therefor are described. The ability to introduce in real time, a variety of isolating structures including pens and barriers offers improved methods of micro-object manipulation in microfluidic devices. The in situ-generated isolation structures may be permanently or temporarily installed.

column12: 인 시츄-생성된 미세유체 격리 구조체들, 키트들, 및 그 이용 방법들
column13: 고체화된 폴리머 네트워크를 편입시키는 인 시츄-생성된 미세유체 격리 구조체들, 준비 및 이용의 방법들, 이를 위한 조성물들, 및 키트들이 설명된다. 펜들 및 장벽들을 포함하는 다양한 격리 구조체들을 실시간으로 도입하기 위한 능력은 미세유체 디바이스들에서의 미세-객체 조작의 개선된 방법들을 제공한다. 인 시츄-생성된 격리 구조체들은 영구적으로 또는 일시적으로 설치될 수도 있다.

column12: Coprocessor context priority
column13: A system may include a plurality of processors and a coprocessor. A plurality of coprocessor context priority registers corresponding to a plurality of contexts supported by the coprocessor may be included. The plurality of processors may use the plurality of contexts, and may program the coprocessor context priority register corresponding to a context with a value specifying a priority of the context relative to other contexts. An arbiter may arbitrate among instructions issued by the plurality of processors based on the priorities in the plurality of coprocessor context priority registers. In one embodiment, real-time threads may be assigned higher priorities than bulk processing tasks, improving bandwidth allocated to the real-time threads as compared to the bulk tasks.

column12: 미세유체 세포 배양
column13: 세포 성장, 생존성, 이동성, 또는 이들의 임의의 조합을 강화시키도록 구성된 기체 성분들 및 영양소들의 제공을 포함하는, 미세유체 디바이스에서 하나 이상의 생물학적 세포들을 배양하기 위한 시스템들, 방법들 및 키트들이 설명된다. 일부 실시형태들에서, 단일의 세포를 배양하는 것은 미세유체 디바이스에서 클론성 집단을 생성할 수도 있다.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR CREATING, EDITING, AND USING MULTI-RELATIONAL ONTOLOGIES
column13: The invention relates to a system and method for creating, editing, using one or more multi-relational ontologies and applying knowledge contained in one or more ontologies to one or more applications. The system may extract concepts, relationships, assertions and other information from a domain specific corpus of documents. The system may also create rule-based assertions that are then curated and published as one or more ontologies that can be used in various ways.

column12: MICROFLUIDIC CELL CULTURE
column13: Systems, methods and kits are described for culturing one or more biological cells in a microfluidic device, including provision of nutrients and gaseous components configured to enhance cell growth, viability, portability, or any combination thereof. In some embodiments, culturing a single cell may produce a clonal population in the microfluidic device.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR CREATING, EDITING, AND USING MULTI-RELATIONAL ONTOLOGIES
column13: The invention relates to a system and method for creating, editing, using one or more multi-relational ontologies and applying knowledge contained in one or more ontologies to one or more applications. The system may extract concepts, relationships, assertions and other information from a domain specific corpus of documents. The system may also create rule-based assertions that are then curated and published as one or more ontologies that can be used in various ways.
